<br>
It might be that this guy-friend feels exactly the same as you do at this point about your relationship with him versus his relationship with his wife.  You said that you'd talked in the past about how this should just be a friendship and not mess up your marriages, and set boundaries.<br>
<br>
Perhaps it's simply time for another talk, to redraw those boundaries to be a little more strict.  That would be the sane first option to me.  I honestly feel that unless the temptation is very great, trying to avoid this person - who's a friend of yours and your husbands, and I'm assuming you're also friendly with his spouse as well - will make matters more strained.<br>
<br>
Besides, if you try to turn your energies back into your own marriage and away from the fun flirting, the issue might take care of itself.  As someone who's still in a &quot;dating&quot; relationship (we're long term, but long distance also, which makes it very much like dating all the time) I'm blessed/cursed with a relationship that's exciting almost all the time we're physically together (limited as it is) because we're always thinking in terms of doing things with one another rather than doing the dishes - those get done in tears after the other has left.<br>
<br>
But the general idea still applies to your interactions with your husband.  Pick a night and do something fun - it doesn't have to expensive, nor does it have to be cheesy.  It could just be going for a drive, going window shopping, walking around town or your neighborhood.  That doesn't necessarily bring you closer together by itself...but it's not a bad start.<br>
<br>
-Brora. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=lilstryven>Lil Stryven</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Big Gnome<br>
